# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chart
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] The **38th Canadian Parliament** was in session from October 4, 2004, until November 29, 2005.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] The membership was set by the 2004 federal election on June 28, 2004, and it changed only somewhat due to resignations and by-elections, but due to the seat distribution, those few changes significantly affected the distribution of power.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] It was dissolved prior to the 2006 election.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] The 38th Canadian Parliament was controlled by a Liberal Party minority under Prime Minister Paul Martin and the 27th Canadian Ministry.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] The Official Opposition was the Conservative Party, led by Stephen Harper.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] See also List of Canadian federal electoral districts for a list of the ridings in this parliament.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] The parliament was dissolved following a vote of non-confidence passed on 28 November by the opposition Conservatives, supported by the New Democratic Party and Bloc Québécois.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] Consequently, a federal election was held on 23 January 2006 to choose the next parliament.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] The 27th Canadian Ministry was formed during the 37th Canadian Parliament and lasted for the entirety of the 28th Parliament.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] In early 2005 Ontario Member of Parliament (MP) Belinda Stronach crossed the floor to the Liberal Party after running for Leader of the Conservative Party of Canada, and coming in second to Stephen Harper.
[src:chart/38th-canadian-parliament] She ended her public relationship with Conservative MP Peter MacKay.
[src:chart/aaron-koblin] Koblin received his MFA from UCLA's Design | Media Arts MFA program and BA from UC Santa Cruz.
[src:chart/aaron-koblin] He is on the advisory board for the UCLA School of Arts and Architecture, and was previously on the board of the non-profit Gray Area Foundation For The Arts GAFFTA in San Francisco.
[src:chart/aaron-koblin] He was the Abramowitz Artist in Residence at MIT in 2010 and the Annenberg Innovator in residence at USC in 2013.
[src:chart/aaron-koblin] Koblin's artworks are part of the permanent collections of the Victoria and Albert Museum (V&A), the Museum of Modern Art (MoMA), and the Centre Georges Pompidou.
[src:chart/aaron-koblin] He has presented at TED, and The World Economic Forum, and his work has been shown at international festivals including Ars Electronica, SIGGRAPH, and the Japan Media Arts Festival.
[src:chart/aaron-koblin] In 2006, his Flight Patterns project received the National Science Foundation's first place award for science visualization.
[src:chart/aaron-koblin] In 2009, he was named to Creativity Magazine's Creativity 50, in 2010 he was one of Esquire Magazine's Best and Brightest and Fast Company's Most Creative People in Business, and in 2011 was one of *Forbes* magazine's 30 under 30.
[src:chart/aaron-koblin] Koblin was an Eyebeam exhibiting artist.
[src:chart/aaron-koblin] In 2014, Koblin was awarded the National Design Award for Interactive Design.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] Ade Olufeko was born in Minneapolis, Minnesota, and spent his formative years in Lagos, Nigeria, living in Surulere during the country’s Second Republic.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] He attended Unilag Staff School for primary education and St.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] Gregory's College in Obalende for secondary school.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] In the mid-1990s, he returned to Minneapolis, where he attended Camden and gave guest lectures to International Baccalaureate peers on cultural perspectives in English literature.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] He later enrolled at Metropolitan State University in Saint Paul, where he studied computer science with a focus on multimedia technologies.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] Olufeko began his career in 1997 with a law internship at Hinshaw & Culbertson, where he assisted with digital integration for legal archiving.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] During the dot-com period, he transitioned into technology, working in interactive design, internet technologies, and hardware at companies including Ameritech, Imation, and IBM.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] While based in Minneapolis in the early to mid-2000s, he worked with musicians in New York City, including Amel Larrieux and Ladybug Mecca, on web design and digital strategy projects.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] He later relocated to New York City and joined Warner Music Group, where he contributed to its digital properties.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] Between 2004 and 2007, Olufeko worked in quality assurance at Shavlik Technologies and Adobe Systems, focusing on software testing and product stability.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] In 2007, he founded Visual Collaborative, a platform for artists and creatives that featured over 150 participants over a decade.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] In 2016, he returned to IBM as a management consultant, working on technology-driven initiatives.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] After relocating to Lagos, Nigeria, Olufeko worked in the creative and technology sectors.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] Prior to settling in Lagos, he undertook consulting projects in Lagos and Abuja.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] He later served as a management consultant for The Avenue Projects.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] From 2021 to 2023, he served as the first chairman of the Creative and Entertainment Group within the Lagos Chamber of Commerce and Industry, where he advocated for policies supporting SMEs and creative enterprises, particularly in intellectual property.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] He is described as an advocate for decentralized technologies in Africa’s creative economy.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] Olufeko has delivered talks at institutions including the University of Oxford, Yale University, and Harvard Business School on topics related to innovation, digital transformation, and Africa’s economy.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] He has also served as a guest moderator at London Business School and Columbia University, and has spoken at institutions including Georgetown University, Carnegie Mellon University, and the Lagos Business School on topics related to technology, creativity, and economic development.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] Self-taught as a digital painter and in mixed-media artistry, Olufeko's creative process as an avocation evolved over a decade.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] His exhibited work explores Africanfuturism and contemporary culture.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] In 2021, he introduced a wax print version of the indigenous Ayo mancala in Ankara fabric, initially producing 200 units for the consumer market.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] He later expanded the product line with Kente and Adire variants distributed across West Africa and its diaspora.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] According to audited data, sales of locally made units exceeded 5,000.During a period of capital flight in Nigeria and a fire outbreak in one of the largest woodcraft communities, part of these proceeds supported artisans and their families.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] Olufeko, discussing knowledge transfer across generations.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] His artwork *Remember To Rise*, a collaboration with London Business School, and *Iyasile Naa*, a project with Oxford University, reflect his integration of technology and cultural narratives into visual storytelling.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] In 2017, Ade Olufeko led a multidisciplinary project documenting Nigeria's Sungbo's Eredo earthworks.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] The team employed blockchain technology for metadata preservation alongside geospatial mapping and local oral history collection.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] As part of the *North Star* Electronic Catalogue for Visual Collaborative, Olufeko authored *Voyager (Vol.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] 4)* in 2019, followed by *TwentyEightyFour (Vol.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] During the same period, he wrote *The Enterprising Young African: Avoiding Pitfalls in Technology and Business (*2019), which examines challenges in Africa’s evolving digital and business landscape.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] Olufeko has trained in several martial arts disciplines, including Wing Chun, Wudang Kung fu, Aikido, Iaido, and boxing, with instruction received in the United States, China, Japan, and Indonesia.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] He trained in Ving Tsun within the Moy Yat lineage of the Ip Man system in New York City under Sifu William Moy.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] During his martial arts training at Luofu Mountain, he was given the Chinese name Fu Qingyun by Shifu Wang Shizhi, a 15th-generation inheritor of the Wudang Sanfeng sect.
[src:chart/ade-olufeko] In 2024, he established the Wing Chun Foundation Lagos, an organization focused on the practice and study of Wing Chun in Lagos, Nigeria, applying its principles to leadership development.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He also founded the science of anthropometry and developed the body mass index (BMI) scale, originally called the Quetelet Index.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] His work on measuring human characteristic to determine the ideal *l'homme moyen* ("the average man"), played a key role in the origins of eugenics.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe was born in Ghent (which, at the time was a part of the new French Republic).
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He was the son of François-Augustin-Jacques-Henri Quetelet, a Frenchman and Anne Françoise Vandervelde, a Flemish woman.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] His father was born at Ham, Picardy, and being of a somewhat adventurous spirit, he crossed the English Channel and became both a British citizen and the secretary of a Scottish nobleman.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In that capacity, he traveled with his employer on the Continent, particularly spending time in Italy.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] At about 31, he settled in Ghent and was employed by the city, where Adolphe was born, the fifth of nine children, several of whom died in childhood.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Francois died when Adolphe was only seven years old.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe studied at the Ghent Lycée, where he afterwards started teaching mathematics in 1815 at the age of 19.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In 1819, he moved to the Athenaeum in Brussels and in the same year he completed his dissertation (*De quibusdam locis geometricis, necnon de curva focal – Of some new properties of the focal distance and some other curves*).
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet received a doctorate in mathematics in 1819 from the University of Ghent.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Shortly thereafter, the young man set out to convince government officials and private donors to build an astronomical observatory in Brussels; he succeeded in 1828.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He became a member of the Royal Academy in 1820.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He lectured at the museum for sciences and letters and at the Belgian Military School.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In 1825, he became a correspondent of the Royal Institute of the Netherlands, in 1827 he became a member.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In 1839, he was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] From 1841 to 1851, he was a supernumerary associate in the institute, and when it became Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences he became foreign member.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In 1850, he was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In 1825, he married Cécile-Virginie Curtet.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet also founded several statistical journals and societies, and was especially interested in creating international cooperation among statisticians.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He encouraged the creation of a statistical section of the British Association for the Advancement of Science (BA), which later became the Royal Statistical Society, of which he became the first overseas member.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In 1853 he chaired both the International Maritime Conference and the first International Statistical Congress.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He was a founding member of the first *Société des douze*.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In 1855, Quetelet developed apoplexy, which diminished but did not end his scientific activity.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He died in Brussels on 17 February 1874, and is buried in the Brussels Cemetery.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] His scientific research encompassed a wide range of different scientific disciplines: meteorology, astronomy, mathematics, statistics, demography, sociology, criminology and history of science.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He made significant contributions to scientific development, but he also wrote several monographs directed to the general public.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He founded the Royal Observatory of Belgium, founded or co-founded several national and international statistical societies and scientific journals, and presided over the first series of the International Statistical Congresses.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was a liberal and an anticlerical, but not an atheist or materialist nor a socialist.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe Quetelet discovered the optical phenomenon Quetelet rings.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] The new science of probability and statistics was mainly used in astronomy at the time, where it was essential to account for measurement errors around means.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] This was done using the method of least squares.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was among the first to apply statistics to social science, planning what he called "social physics".
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He was keenly aware of the overwhelming complexity of social phenomena, and the many variables that needed measurement.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] His goal was to understand the statistical laws underlying such phenomena as crime rates, marriage rates or suicide rates.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He wanted to explain the values of these variables by other social factors.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] These ideas were rather controversial among other scientists at the time who held that it contradicted the concept of freedom of choice.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] His most influential book was *Sur l'homme et le développement de ses facultés, ou Essai de physique sociale*, published in 1835 (In English translation, it is titled *Treatise on Man*, but a literal translation would be "On Man and the Development of his Faculties, or Essay on Social Physics").
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In it, he outlines the project of a social physics and describes his concept of the "average man" (*l'homme moyen*) who is characterized by the mean values of measured variables that follow a normal distribution.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He collected data about many such variables.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet wrote about these values as "ideals" with deviations from them as being less than or more than ideal.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] He saw the average body as an ideal beauty and something to be desired and his work was influential on Francis Galton who coined the term *eugenics*.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet's student Pierre François Verhulst developed the logistic function in the 1830s as a model of population growth; see Logistic function § History for details.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Adolphe Quetelet also had a significant influence on Florence Nightingale who shared with him a religious view of statistics which saw understanding statistics as revealing the work of God in addition to statistics being a force of good administration.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Nightingale met Quetelet in person at the 1860 International Statistical Congress in London, and they corresponded for years afterwards.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was an influential figure in criminology.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Along with Andre-Michel Guerry, he helped to establish the cartographic school and positivist schools of criminology which made extensive use of statistical techniques.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Through statistical analysis, Quetelet gained insight into the relationships between crime and other social factors.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Among his findings were strong relationships between age and crime, as well as gender and crime.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Other influential factors he found included climate, poverty, education, and alcohol consumption, with his research findings published in *Of the Development of the Propensity to Crime*.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In his 1835 text on social physics, he presented his theory of human variance around the average, showing human traits were distributed according to a normal curve.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] The existence of such variation provided the basis for later writers, including Darwin, to argue that natural populations contained sufficient variability for artificial or natural selection to operate.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] In terms of influence over later public health agendas, one of Quetelet's lasting legacies was the establishment of a simple measure for classifying people's weight relative to an ideal for their height.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] His proposal, the body mass index (or Quetelet index), has endured with minor variations to the present day.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Anthropometric data is used in modern applications and referenced in the development of every consumer-based product.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] Quetelet was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society (ForMemRS) in 1839.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] The asteroid 1239 Queteleta is named after him.
[src:chart/adolphe-quetelet] The title of Quetelet professor at Columbia University is awarded in his name.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] An **aeronautical chart** is a map designed to assist in the navigation of aircraft, much as nautical charts do for watercraft, or a roadmap does for drivers.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] Using these charts and other tools, pilots are able to determine their position, safe altitude, best route to a destination, navigation aids along the way, alternative landing areas in case of an in-flight emergency, and other useful information such as radio frequencies and airspace boundaries.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] There are charts for all land masses on Earth, and long-distance charts for trans-oceanic travel.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] Specific charts are used for each phase of a flight and may vary from a map of a particular airport facility to an overview of the instrument routes covering an entire continent (e.g., global navigation charts), and many types in between.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] Visual flight charts are categorized according to their scale, which is proportional to the size of the area covered by one map.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] The amount of detail is necessarily reduced when larger areas are represented on a map.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] When an aircraft is flying under instrument flight rules (IFR), the pilot will often have no visual reference to the ground, and must therefore rely on external (e.g.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] Although in some situations air traffic control may issue radar vectors to direct an aircraft's path, this is usually done to facilitate traffic flow, and will not be the sole means of navigating to an important point, such as the position from which an aircraft commences its approach to landing.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] Charts used for IFR flights contain an abundance of information regarding locations of waypoints, known as "fixes", which are defined by measurements from electronic beacons of various types, as well as the routes connecting these waypoints.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] Only limited topographic information is found on IFR charts, although the minimum safe altitudes available on the routes are shown.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] En-route low- and high-altitude charts are published with a scale that depends upon the density of navigation information required in the vicinity.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] Information from IFR charts is often programmed into a flight management system or autopilot, which eases the task of following (or deviating from) a flight plan.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] Terminal procedure publications such as standard terminal arrival plates, standard instrument departure plates and other documentation provide detailed information for arrival, departure and taxiing at each approved airport having instrument capabilities of some sort.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] Aeronautical charts may be purchased at fixed-base operators (FBOs), internet supply sources, or catalogs of aeronautical gear.
[src:chart/aeronautical-chart] They may also be viewed online from the Federal Aviation Administration.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] Alan MacEachren received a B.A. in geography in 1974 at the Ohio University, an M.A. in geography in 1976 from the University of Kansas and a Ph.D. in geography 1979 from University of Kansas.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] From 1979 to 1983, he was assistant professor of geography at the Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University and Director of the Department of Geography Cartography Laboratory.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] From 1980 to 1983, he was Director of the Department of Geography Spatial Analysis Laboratory, Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] In 1983, he became assistant professor of geography at the University of Colorado-Boulder and in 1985 switched to associate professor of Geography and Director of the Deasy GeoGraphics Laboratory at the Pennsylvania State University, where he worked until 1992.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] From 1992, he was professor of geography, and since 1998 director, GeoVISTA Center, Department of Geography, Penn State University.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] In Fall 2007, he was visiting professor, Department of Computer Science, Stanford University, and since 2007 also Affiliate Professor of Information Sciences and Technology, Penn State University.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] Awards for Alan MacEachren in 2004-2007 include the E.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] Miller Professor of Geography, College of Earth and Mineral Science, Penn State University.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] He became an Honorary Fellow of the International Cartographic Association in 2005, making him only the sixth Fellow from the U.S. since 1974.
[src:chart/alan-maceachren] In 2004, he was also recognized for Exceptional Scholarly Contributions to the Practice of Cartography, by the Canadian Cartographic Association.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] Inselberg started his career at the Biological Computer Laboratory based at University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] He was part of a cybernetics group working on biomathematics developing mathematical models of the ear, neural networks, and computer models for vision and non-linear analysis, gaining a PhD in mathematics and physics.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] During this period he participated in the Symposium on Principles of Self-Organization.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] He is particularly noted for his work on parallel coordinates (||-coords), which he proposed in 1959, for the visualization of multidimensional geometries (as in linear algebra) and multivariate problems.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] Later he attended Whittingehame College in Brighton, England.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] He attended the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign (UIUC) receiving a B.Sc. in Aeronautical Engineering.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] Together with Gary van Sant, and two other students under the guidance of Paul Torda, they founded the University of Illinois Rocket Society in 1953; four years prior to Sputnik.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] Continuing his studies at UIUC he obtained in 1965 a Ph.D. in Applied Mathematics and Physics under the joint guidance of Ray Langebartel and Heinz von Foerster.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] Inselberg held senior research positions at IBM where he developed a mathematical model of the ear (cochlea) (Time November 1974) and later collision-avoidance algorithms for air traffic control (3 USA patents).
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] Concurrently he had joint appointments at UCLA, USC, Technion and Ben Gurion University.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] Since 1995 he has been a professor at the School of Mathematical Sciences of Tel Aviv University.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] He was elected senior fellow at the San Diego Supercomputing Center in 1996.
[src:chart/alfred-inselberg] His textbook on "Parallel Coordinates: Visual Multidimensional Geometry", was published by Springer.
[src:chart/chart] A **chart** (sometimes known as a **graph**) is a graphical representation for data and information visualization, in which "the data is represented by symbols, such as bars in a bar chart, lines in a line chart, or slices in a pie chart".
[src:chart/chart] A chart can represent tabular numeric data, functions or some kinds of quality structure and provides different info.
[src:chart/chart] Charts are often used to ease understanding of large quantities of data and the relationships between parts of the data.
[src:chart/chart] Charts can usually be read more quickly than the raw data.
[src:chart/chart] They are used in a wide variety of fields, and can be created by hand (often on graph paper) or by computer using a charting application.
[src:chart/chart] Certain types of charts are more useful for presenting a given data set than others.
[src:chart/chart] For example, data that presents percentages in different groups (such as "satisfied, not satisfied, unsure") are often displayed in a pie chart, but maybe more easily understood when presented in a horizontal bar chart.
[src:chart/chart] On the other hand, data that represents numbers that change over a period of time (such as "annual revenue from 1990 to 2000") might be best shown as a line chart.
[src:chart/chart] A chart can take a large variety of forms.
[src:chart/chart] However, there are common features that provide the chart with its ability to extract meaning from data.
[src:chart/chart] Typically the data in a chart is represented graphically since humans can infer meaning from pictures more quickly than from text.
[src:chart/chart] Thus, the text is generally used only to annotate the data.
[src:chart/chart] One of the most important uses of text in a graph is the **title**.
[src:chart/chart] A graph's title usually appears above the main graphic and provides a succinct description of what the data in the graph refers to.
[src:chart/chart] Dimensions in the data are often displayed on **axes**.
[src:chart/chart] If a horizontal and a vertical axis are used, they are usually referred to as the x-axis and y-axis.
[src:chart/chart] Each axis will have a **scale**, denoted by periodic graduations and usually accompanied by numerical or categorical indications.
[src:chart/chart] Each axis will typically also have a label displayed outside or beside it, briefly describing the dimension represented.
[src:chart/chart] If the scale is numerical, the label will often be suffixed with the unit of that scale in parentheses.
[src:chart/chart] For example, "Distance traveled (m)" is a typical x-axis label and would mean that the distance traveled, in units of meters, is related to the horizontal position of the data within the chart.
[src:chart/chart] Within the graph, a **grid** of lines may appear to aid in the visual alignment of data.
[src:chart/chart] The grid can be enhanced by visually emphasizing the lines at regular or significant graduations.
[src:chart/chart] The emphasized lines are then called major gridlines, and the remainder is minor grid lines.
[src:chart/chart] A chart's data can appear in all manner of formats and may include individual textual **labels** describing the datum associated with the indicated position in the chart.
[src:chart/chart] The data may appear as dots or shapes, connected or unconnected, and in any combination of colors and patterns.
[src:chart/chart] In addition, inferences or points of interest can be overlaid directly on the graph to further aid information extraction.
[src:chart/chart] When the data appearing in a chart contains multiple variables, the chart may include a **legend** (also known as a **key**).
[src:chart/chart] A legend contains a list of the variables appearing in the chart and an example of their appearance.
[src:chart/chart] This information allows the data from each variable to be identified in the chart.
[src:chart/chart] Some specific charts have become well known by effectively explaining a phenomenon or idea.
[src:chart/chart] There are dozens of other types of charts.
[src:chart/chart] While charts can be drawn by hand, computer software is often used to automatically produce a chart based on entered data.
[src:chart/chart] For examples of commonly used software tools, see List of charting software.
